03:37.333 --> 03:39.567
Every stop can seem like
another country,

03:39.600 --> 03:40.900
another region.

03:40.933 --> 03:44.233
♪

03:44.267 --> 03:46.300
Get off at Roosevelt Avenue,

03:46.333 --> 03:48.633
and you are gonna eat well
for sure.

03:48.667 --> 03:52.300
Example: this cart sells
Ecuadorian food.

03:52.333 --> 03:55.233
Hornado: roast pork
with sublime crispy skin

03:55.267 --> 03:56.733
straight from heaven.

03:56.767 --> 03:58.998
Crunch, cru... Oh, that's the
sound of victory right there.

04:00.333 --> 04:04.567
Morcilla: blood sausage
with potato cakes.

04:04.600 --> 04:06.567
Oh, man.
That's looking really good.

04:06.600 --> 04:07.567
Gracias.

04:12.433 --> 04:13.760
This is a working-class
neighborhood.

04:13.767 --> 04:15.900
People coming to and from work.
Yep.

04:15.933 --> 04:19.533
How often do you think
the average person

04:19.567 --> 04:21.067
eats at one of these things?

04:21.100 --> 04:22.633
Lot of, like, the day laborers,

04:22.667 --> 04:24.493
a lot of the men that are here,
they might live in

04:24.500 --> 04:26.567
these tiny apartments
with a tiny shared kitchen.

04:26.600 --> 04:27.967
They can't cook.
Right.

04:28.000 --> 04:29.260
They're not gonna
go into the restaurants.

04:29.267 --> 04:30.567
They don't have time for that.

04:30.600 --> 04:33.067
So it's... for them,
it might be even more

04:33.100 --> 04:35.067
that they're eating
on the streets.

04:35.100 --> 04:38.733
Sean Basinski is the director
of the Street Vendor Project.

04:38.767 --> 04:41.000
Prior to going to law school,
he built a pushcart

04:41.033 --> 04:44.200
and sold burritos on the corner
of 52nd and Park.

04:44.233 --> 04:46.067
He founded SVP
with a small grant

04:46.100 --> 04:48.300
from Yale University Law School.

04:48.333 --> 04:50.667
He lives in a tenement walkup
apartment in Manhattan

04:50.700 --> 04:52.400
with a bathtub in the kitchen,

04:52.433 --> 04:54.900
you know, like most lawyers.

04:54.933 --> 04:56.833
So if we did,
like, a mile in here.

05:03.333 --> 05:04.500
Yeah.

05:04.533 --> 05:07.167
What would my options be
nationality-wise?

05:07.200 --> 05:08.593
It's incredible.
I mean, you can have Tibetan

05:08.600 --> 05:10.667
street food, and then there's
Colombian arepas.

05:10.700 --> 05:11.900
If you go up into Flushing,

05:11.933 --> 05:13.633
and then there is
the Chinese barbecue carts.

05:13.667 --> 05:14.993
I don't know of
anyplace in New York,

05:15.000 --> 05:16.667
maybe even the world
or the country,

05:16.700 --> 05:18.426
that you can have
such diversity on the street.

05:18.433 --> 05:20.833
Matt Shapiro is another
lawyer who represents

05:20.867 --> 05:22.667
street vendors
when they need legal help,

05:22.700 --> 05:25.000
which in our nanny state
current reality

05:25.033 --> 05:27.400
is all too often.

05:27.433 --> 05:29.167
Now, generally speaking,

05:29.200 --> 05:32.333
to open up a cart on the street,
you need a license?

05:32.367 --> 05:34.567
You have to have a license
for yourself,

05:34.600 --> 05:36.900
and then you have to have
a permit for the cart itself.

05:36.933 --> 05:37.967
That's the problem.

05:38.000 --> 05:39.167
And any spot?

05:39.200 --> 05:40.367
Generally speaking, yes,

05:40.400 --> 05:41.967
although there's lots
of restrictions.

05:42.000 --> 05:43.567
Manhattan is very much
the, you know,

05:43.600 --> 05:47.167
"not in my backyard"
neighborhood in a lot of ways.

05:47.200 --> 05:49.033
I mean, for this reason,
Manhattan, in my view,

05:49.067 --> 05:50.900
is a lot less interesting
than Queens.

05:50.933 --> 05:52.533
- Right.
- This is a wonderland.

05:52.567 --> 05:53.533
Yeah.

05:53.567 --> 05:55.800
I mean, look what we got here.

05:58.433 --> 06:00.467
You know, they're trying to
change it, though.

06:00.500 --> 06:01.833
And the more it does change,

06:01.867 --> 06:03.733
the more the vendors
are threatened, you know?

06:03.767 --> 06:06.400
There's all this talk about
"cleaning up" Roosevelt Avenue.

06:06.433 --> 06:07.900
You know what that means.

06:07.933 --> 06:10.233
If you get higher rent,
nicer buildings,

06:10.267 --> 06:12.700
they're not gonna want
a street cart out in front.

06:12.733 --> 06:14.493
That's sometimes the problems
that vendors face.

06:14.500 --> 06:16.400
Even if the spot
is completely legal,

06:16.433 --> 06:19.400
and we see it all the time,
where there's building managers

06:19.433 --> 06:20.726
that come out and say,
"Hey, you know,

06:20.733 --> 06:21.826
you gotta move;
you can't be here."

06:21.833 --> 06:23.033
They even call the police.

06:23.067 --> 06:26.467
So what happens if that...
When that occurs?

06:26.500 --> 06:29.400
When it was me, you know,
the young kid out of college,

06:29.433 --> 06:31.200
I was ready for that.
Right.

06:31.233 --> 06:33.500
But if you're an immigrant
who doesn't speak any English

06:33.533 --> 06:35.500
and is realistically scared,

06:35.533 --> 06:37.667
and they tell you to move,
well, you're gonna move.

06:37.700 --> 06:40.567
♪

06:40.600 --> 06:45.067
In a perfect world, how many
of these would there be?

06:45.100 --> 06:46.493
I think the more diverse
street food

06:46.500 --> 06:47.667
we could have, the better.

06:47.700 --> 06:49.500
The more pathways
we can provide for people

06:49.533 --> 06:51.567
to come and start a business
and hopefully, you know,

06:51.600 --> 06:53.000
after five or ten years,

06:53.033 --> 06:55.467
maybe they'll have a restaurant,
right?

07:00.467 --> 07:03.133
I mean, we don't say there are
too many restaurants, do we?

07:03.167 --> 07:05.367
So why too many food vendors?

07:05.400 --> 07:07.131
Too many affordable
restaurants, goddamn it.

07:22.167 --> 07:24.033
Hey, what's up, New York City?

07:24.067 --> 07:25.033
How y'all doing?

07:27.100 --> 07:29.033
♪ Inshallah, mashallah

07:29.067 --> 07:31.033
♪ Hopefully no martial law

07:31.067 --> 07:33.033
♪ Hai Allah, yo yallah

07:33.067 --> 07:35.200
♪ Let's rock a show
in Ramallah ♪

