08:50.033 --> 08:53.567
Himanshu Suri
is better known as Heems,

08:53.600 --> 08:56.900
half of the rap duo
known as the Swet Shop Boys.

08:56.933 --> 08:58.900
He was born and raised
in Queens,

08:58.933 --> 09:00.633
a living, breathing example

09:00.667 --> 09:04.067
of the glorious mash-up
that is this borough.

09:04.100 --> 09:05.067
♪

09:05.100 --> 09:06.567
So it seems just right

09:06.600 --> 09:08.067
that a first-generation
Indian dude

09:08.100 --> 09:09.833
takes me to a Chinese
dumpling spot

09:09.867 --> 09:11.533
close to his Hindu temple.

09:11.567 --> 09:15.133
Yu Garden Dumplings is
everything you need in life.

09:15.167 --> 09:17.400
So born and raised, Queens?

09:17.433 --> 09:18.733
- Yep.
- What neighborhood?

09:18.767 --> 09:20.567
Most of my life
I've been in Glen Oaks

09:20.600 --> 09:22.967
and Bellerose, which is,
like, further east.

09:23.000 --> 09:24.800
Largely or mostly Indian?

09:24.833 --> 09:26.667
Our neighborhood
is mostly Punjabi

09:26.700 --> 09:29.500
and then there was Christians
from Kerala, Malayali,

09:29.533 --> 09:31.733
and Pakistanis.
Those three.

09:31.767 --> 09:33.900
And next non-Indian
neighborhood over?

09:33.933 --> 09:35.333
More like Guyanese,

09:35.367 --> 09:37.367
still Indo-Caribbean.
Right. Right.

09:37.400 --> 09:38.733
And then the other neighborhood,

09:38.767 --> 09:40.800
like, whiter but still Indian.

09:40.833 --> 09:43.233
So it's hard to escape us
in Queens,

09:43.267 --> 09:44.700
which is why I like it here.

09:44.733 --> 09:46.833
♪

09:46.867 --> 09:48.667
Spicy beef and tripes:

09:48.700 --> 09:51.900
boiled pig tongue and tripe
marinated in sugar and soy,

09:51.933 --> 09:53.400
served cold with chili oil.

09:53.433 --> 09:55.567
Traditional Indian food at home?

09:55.600 --> 09:56.967
What about outside the house?

09:57.000 --> 09:58.733
Because the food's
so good at home,

09:58.767 --> 10:00.567
we don't really go out
to eat Indian food,

10:00.600 --> 10:02.367
'cause it would just be my mom
going, "Pssh!"

10:02.400 --> 10:03.593
I could make
better dal than this."

10:03.600 --> 10:04.867
- Right.
- So...

10:04.900 --> 10:06.193
I'm in New York, man;
it was, like, lo mein

10:06.200 --> 10:07.967
and pizza when we weren't
eating Indian food.

10:08.000 --> 10:14.000
Lion's head meatballs:
pork, ginger, soy.

10:14.033 --> 10:15.333
So we used to come to Flushing

10:15.367 --> 10:16.900
even when we moved out
further east

10:16.933 --> 10:18.700
because they didn't have
grocery stores there.

10:18.733 --> 10:20.033
My temple is over here,

10:20.067 --> 10:22.167
and so even as we moved further
out to Long Island,

10:22.200 --> 10:24.667
we always end up coming back
to here or Jackson Heights,

10:24.700 --> 10:26.833
which are like these
first places you come.

10:26.867 --> 10:29.026
Sometimes I joke, I mean, Queens
is so great and so diverse,

10:29.033 --> 10:30.593
but it's also 'cause
the airports are here.

10:30.600 --> 10:33.200
So it's just like
you get off of a 16-hour flight

10:33.233 --> 10:34.660
with no money in your pocket
from India,

10:34.667 --> 10:35.860
and you're like,
"Where am I gonna live?"

10:35.867 --> 10:37.000
Well, I'm already here.

10:37.033 --> 10:38.567
"So let's start with this place."

10:38.600 --> 10:39.100
♪

10:45.400 --> 10:47.167
Soup dumplings:
piping hot

10:47.200 --> 10:51.533
and filled with ground pork
and near boiling broth.

10:51.567 --> 10:52.833
This is why I come here.

10:52.867 --> 10:54.167
Yeah, this is dumplings.

10:54.200 --> 10:55.367
Oh, yeah.

10:55.400 --> 10:56.733
So when you were growing up,

10:56.767 --> 10:59.067
what was
the ethno-national breakdown

10:59.100 --> 11:01.333
of a typical class in school?

11:01.367 --> 11:02.926
My high school
was a public high school,

11:02.933 --> 11:06.500
but it was maybe 70%
East and South Asian,

11:06.533 --> 11:08.333
mostly Chinese and Korean.

11:08.367 --> 11:10.233
And all those kids
end up going to Harvard.

11:10.267 --> 11:11.867
All those kids
end up going to NYU

11:11.900 --> 11:13.333
and those types of schools.

11:13.367 --> 11:16.000
And, you know,
if the American dream is alive,

11:16.033 --> 11:18.467
I think it's alive
in places like Queens.

11:18.500 --> 11:19.733
What do you mean by that?

11:19.767 --> 11:22.033
That there still are people
coming here with nothing

11:22.067 --> 11:23.567
and making something out of it.

11:23.600 --> 11:27.667
And as I kind of lose hope
in the idea of,

11:27.700 --> 11:29.467
like, diversity
as a positive thing

11:29.500 --> 11:32.000
or the idea of America
as an open place,

11:32.033 --> 11:35.367
I think in a place with so much
race and diversity,

11:35.400 --> 11:38.633
it gets in the way less here
than it does in other places.

11:38.667 --> 11:42.167
Will America as a whole look
sooner or later like Queens?

11:42.200 --> 11:46.133
I guess 2042 is the year
that people of color

11:46.167 --> 11:48.033
become the majority
in this country.

11:48.067 --> 11:49.033
Yep.

11:49.067 --> 11:50.360
Seems like
a long, long time away.

11:50.367 --> 11:51.767
But yeah, that is the hope.

12:05.167 --> 12:05.667
♪

12:35.833 --> 12:36.333
♪

12:54.367 --> 12:56.300
Get lost in Flushing
for a while,

12:56.333 --> 12:58.500
and behold the awesomeness.

13:01.533 --> 13:02.033
♪

13:19.667 --> 13:20.167
♪

13:43.500 --> 13:44.000
♪

13:53.200 --> 13:54.500
♪

13:54.533 --> 13:56.533
If you're looking for
amazing Chinese food

13:56.567 --> 13:58.533
or Korean just like home,

13:58.567 --> 14:00.367
well, Flushing is the place.

14:00.400 --> 14:03.533
♪

14:03.567 --> 14:07.333
This joint is high on the list,
Geo Si Gi.

14:07.367 --> 14:09.200
Cheers..

14:09.233 --> 14:11.900
Josh Smookler and Cosme Aguilar

14:11.933 --> 14:13.700
are both chefs and restaurateurs

14:13.733 --> 14:15.700
operating in Queens.

14:15.733 --> 14:17.867
Josh, a Korean man
who was adopted

14:17.900 --> 14:19.700
and raised by a Jewish family

14:19.733 --> 14:21.167
owns the wildly popular

14:21.200 --> 14:23.533
Long Island City restaurant
Mu Ramen.

14:23.567 --> 14:24.560
Did it take off right away?

14:24.567 --> 14:25.593
It was successful right away?

14:25.600 --> 14:27.733
Yes, pretty much immediately.

14:27.767 --> 14:29.260
You know, I was cooking
out of my house.

14:29.267 --> 14:31.500
Then we were transporting all
to this bagel shop.

14:31.533 --> 14:35.367
We served from 7:00 to 9:30,
ten seats at a time.

14:35.400 --> 14:37.333
It was me in the kitchen;
my wife out in the front.

14:37.367 --> 14:40.500
And one day, somebody texted me,
goes, "Congratulations."

14:40.533 --> 14:41.667
I go, "For what?"

14:41.700 --> 14:43.900
They go, "Pete Wells
just gave you"

14:43.933 --> 14:46.167
number one ramen
in New York City."

14:46.200 --> 14:47.733
So "New York Times" loves you.

14:47.767 --> 14:50.167
And I saw the article,
and I started crying.

14:50.200 --> 14:53.500
♪

14:53.533 --> 14:56.033
Cosme is the owner
of Casa Enrique,

14:56.067 --> 14:57.667
also in Long Island City.

14:57.700 --> 15:00.133
It's the only
Mexican restaurant in New York

15:00.167 --> 15:01.667
with a Michelin star.

15:01.700 --> 15:02.760
You didn't even do
the smart thing.

15:02.767 --> 15:03.760
The smart thing, of course,

15:03.767 --> 15:05.167
would be to make
shitty Mexican food

15:05.200 --> 15:06.533
because we know that Americans

15:06.567 --> 15:08.200
will always buy
shitty Mexican food.

15:08.233 --> 15:10.567
You started making
really sophisticated,

15:10.600 --> 15:12.167
really interesting Mexican food.

15:12.200 --> 15:13.467
Well, why?

15:13.500 --> 15:15.500
My brother come up with the idea

15:15.533 --> 15:18.333
to open a Mexican restaurant.

15:18.367 --> 15:19.867
And I told my brother, "Come on",

15:19.900 --> 15:22.467
I'll never cook Mexican food,
like, for restaurant."

15:22.500 --> 15:25.833
So I started cooking for six
months at home every single day,

15:25.867 --> 15:27.567
trying to do different things,

15:27.600 --> 15:30.567
and finally
we open a Mexican restaurant.

15:30.600 --> 15:32.233
But then you got
a Michelin star.

15:32.267 --> 15:33.233
Yeah.

15:33.267 --> 15:34.333
For three years in a row.

15:34.367 --> 15:35.333
Nice.

15:35.367 --> 15:36.533
Both are fantastic,

15:36.567 --> 15:38.900
but tonight we're eating Korean.

15:38.933 --> 15:41.167
Gamja Tang: pork neck bone soup

15:41.200 --> 15:44.833
with rice cakes, pork belly,
kimchi, and spicy radish.

15:44.867 --> 15:47.333
And kimchi and oysters.

15:47.367 --> 15:50.833
So this dish right here,
the Gamja Tang,

15:50.867 --> 15:53.667
was the dish I had,
like, three years ago.

15:53.700 --> 15:56.300
It literally transplanted me
back to Korea.

15:56.333 --> 15:58.300
Yeah, but how old were you
when you left?

15:58.333 --> 16:00.133
When I came to America,
I was six.

16:00.167 --> 16:01.567
Were you raised observant Jew?

16:01.600 --> 16:02.667
- Orthodox, yeah.
- Orth...

16:02.700 --> 16:03.900
You were raised Orthodox.

16:03.933 --> 16:05.500
You still with the program?

16:05.533 --> 16:06.500
No, not at all.

16:06.533 --> 16:07.733
I'm eating pork right now.

16:07.767 --> 16:09.067
Yeah, that's tough.

16:09.100 --> 16:11.000
I mean, 'cause, you know,
Koreans are pork crazy.

16:11.033 --> 16:12.493
Korean food,
where I didn't have much of it

16:12.500 --> 16:14.833
growing up at all...
In fact, kimchi was, like,

16:14.867 --> 16:16.167
shunned from our household

16:16.200 --> 16:17.967
because it stunk up
the whole house.

16:18.000 --> 16:19.193
Well, it's just not kosher too.

16:19.200 --> 16:20.226
And it's not kosher either,
so they...

16:20.233 --> 16:21.733
- With the shellfish in there.
- Yeah.

16:21.767 --> 16:23.567
But now I still make
Korean-style ramen

16:23.600 --> 16:25.500
and then I have
a matzo ball ramen.

16:25.533 --> 16:28.300
Being raised Jewish,
can't help it.

16:28.333 --> 16:32.300
I think as cooks, we always go
gravitate to what our DNA is.

16:32.333 --> 16:34.067
So when are you opening
a Korean restaurant?

16:34.100 --> 16:35.900
I don't know anything
about Korean food.

16:36.933 --> 16:37.967
I just know I like it.

16:38.000 --> 16:39.800
I gravitate
towards those flavors.

16:39.833 --> 16:40.333
♪

16:47.933 --> 16:50.833
Galbi: short ribs
marinated in soy,

16:50.867 --> 16:52.567
garlic, and sesame oil.

16:52.600 --> 16:54.567
Then grilled.

16:54.600 --> 16:55.900
Meat candy.

16:55.933 --> 16:58.167
♪

16:58.200 --> 16:59.833
You ever investigate
other neighborhoods?

16:59.867 --> 17:02.167
The number of immigrants
all over the world,

17:02.200 --> 17:03.900
I mean, is, you know,
extraordinary.

17:03.933 --> 17:05.633
This funny thing.
I was...

17:05.666 --> 17:09.500
I have Caucasians
working the line.

17:09.532 --> 17:10.500
Yeah.

17:10.532 --> 17:11.826
And then the Asians come in,
they go,

17:11.833 --> 17:13.000
"Oh, this isn't good.

17:13.032 --> 17:14.093
You got a bunch of white guys."

17:14.099 --> 17:15.166
I'm like, "What?"

17:15.200 --> 17:16.633
I'm racist like that too.

17:16.666 --> 17:18.200
- Really?
- Yeah, I'm totally like that.

17:18.233 --> 17:20.000
If I walk into
a sushi restaurant,

17:20.032 --> 17:21.967
I make racist assumptions
about the place

17:22.000 --> 17:23.333
if they're not Japanese.

17:23.367 --> 17:25.532
Do you do the same thing
when you go to a restaurant

17:25.567 --> 17:27.500
and you see, like,
let's say a Korean restaurant,

17:27.532 --> 17:28.833
and if you only see
white people,

17:28.867 --> 17:31.000
then what do you think,
it's not legit?

17:31.033 --> 17:32.333
Eating at the Korean restaurant?

17:32.367 --> 17:34.167
- Yeah.
- You want the truth?

17:34.200 --> 17:35.167
Yeah.

17:35.200 --> 17:36.239
Of course I want the truth.

17:39.233 --> 17:39.733
♪

17:52.000 --> 17:52.500
♪

18:14.733 --> 18:17.400
I'm an usher now
for the Metro Christian Center.

18:20.433 --> 18:20.933
♪

18:36.400 --> 18:41.367
Some people say
it's the most famous place

18:41.400 --> 18:42.500
you've never heard of.

18:42.533 --> 18:44.367
That's where we are.

18:44.400 --> 18:46.967
Well, when you start getting out
to the detail of it,

18:47.000 --> 18:48.867
this is historic Neir's Tavern.

18:48.900 --> 18:50.633
Back in the 1820s,

18:50.667 --> 18:52.633
when Queens
was still mostly farmland

18:52.667 --> 18:54.567
and livestock
rather than the 7 train

18:54.600 --> 18:57.400
was what rumbled down
what became Jamaica Avenue,

18:57.433 --> 19:00.433
the manager of a racetrack
called the Union Course

19:00.467 --> 19:03.033
opened a nearby tavern
to accommodate the gamblers

19:03.067 --> 19:06.033
and layabouts
who frequented his track.

19:06.067 --> 19:08.033
It was called
the Blue Pump Room.

19:08.067 --> 19:10.667
In later iterations
it became the Old Abbey,

19:10.700 --> 19:12.333
the Union Course Tavern,

19:12.367 --> 19:14.533
and finally Neir's Tavern.

19:14.567 --> 19:16.367
The Neir family, German émigrés,

19:16.400 --> 19:19.367
added a bowling alley,
a ballroom, and a hotel

19:19.400 --> 19:22.200
after the racetrack closed
in 1898

19:22.233 --> 19:25.167
and renamed the place
Neir's Social Hall.

19:25.200 --> 19:27.033
Today it's owned by this man,

19:27.067 --> 19:29.900
lieutenant Loy Gordon
of the FDNY.

19:29.933 --> 19:31.333
You were born in Jamaica?

19:31.367 --> 19:32.333
That's a funny thing.

19:32.367 --> 19:34.333
I'm from the island of Jamaica,

19:34.367 --> 19:37.467
and I moved to Jamaica, Queens.

19:37.500 --> 19:39.567
Why, uh... why Jamaica Queens?

19:39.600 --> 19:41.000
Well, my mom was here.

19:41.033 --> 19:42.193
What did your mom do
for a living?

19:42.200 --> 19:43.567
What kind of work was she doing?

19:43.600 --> 19:45.200
You know, she was...
Didn't have

19:45.233 --> 19:47.033
all the education in the world.

19:47.067 --> 19:49.700
Uh, so you just had to do
odds and ends,

19:49.733 --> 19:52.533
had to clean floors
and, uh, just do

19:52.567 --> 19:54.533
whatever she had to do
to get things going.

19:54.567 --> 19:56.833
I think it's pretty
much the similar story

19:56.867 --> 19:59.300
of immigrants that
come to the United States.

19:59.333 --> 20:02.867
They come and work hard because
it's the land of opportunity,

20:02.900 --> 20:06.667
and they find a way to kind of
make it out of the rut.

20:06.700 --> 20:07.667
Yep.

20:07.700 --> 20:09.800
Or at least using that
platform to have

20:09.833 --> 20:11.867
someone like me...
Like their offspring

20:11.900 --> 20:15.233
become a little bit more,
right, than they were.

20:15.267 --> 20:15.767
♪

20:19.533 --> 20:21.200
Ordinarily, the story is,

20:21.233 --> 20:23.367
"I'm a regular beer drinker
at this joint,

20:23.400 --> 20:25.367
"and the thought of it
disappearing

20:25.400 --> 20:26.500
"is, like, unbearable to me.

20:26.533 --> 20:27.833
Where am I gonna drink now?"

20:27.867 --> 20:29.700
But you're not that...
That's not your story.

20:29.733 --> 20:31.867
I knew that this place was
important, you know?

20:31.900 --> 20:33.367
I just felt something special.

20:33.400 --> 20:35.500
And being someone
that's from Queens,

20:35.533 --> 20:38.300
something that's special
like this shouldn't disappear.

20:38.333 --> 20:41.800
♪

20:41.833 --> 20:43.533
It was three days
from closing down

20:43.567 --> 20:44.833
when I walked into the place.

20:44.867 --> 20:45.833
Wow.

20:45.867 --> 20:47.167
The way it's located, someone

20:47.200 --> 20:48.833
has to tell you
about Neir's Tavern.

20:48.867 --> 20:50.633
Someone has to say, you know,

20:50.667 --> 20:53.167
"It's around the corner,
to the left, to the right."

20:53.200 --> 20:54.500
And if someone
tell you about it,

20:54.533 --> 20:57.200
I think they think
you're worthy enough to discover

20:57.233 --> 20:59.667
such a historic, you know,
cool little place.

20:59.700 --> 21:02.000
Now, it's historic
for a lot of reasons,

21:02.033 --> 21:04.067
not least, in my mind,

21:04.100 --> 21:06.667
because the greatest
American film

21:06.700 --> 21:08.900
ever made was shot here.

21:12.267 --> 21:13.367
A lot of it was shot here.

21:13.400 --> 21:14.733
I mean, it was...
About 15%.

21:14.767 --> 21:17.000
Okay, so what was shot...
Which scenes were shot here?

21:17.033 --> 21:20.000
It was a very pivotal moment
of the movie.

21:20.033 --> 21:21.333
Okay, that's the...

21:21.367 --> 21:23.067
Wait, wait, wait, wait.
Let me... let me...

21:23.100 --> 21:24.500
Let me remember it.

21:24.533 --> 21:26.500
He's... Is he right there
or is he right here?

21:26.533 --> 21:28.026
- Where you're sitting.
- He's right here.

21:28.033 --> 21:30.667
And he just looks over
at Morrie,

21:30.700 --> 21:32.833
and you know he's decided
Morrie's going.

21:32.867 --> 21:34.000
And if Morrie's going,

21:34.033 --> 21:35.360
might as well just
knock everybody else...

21:35.367 --> 21:36.860
Well, no, Morrie was a problem
from the beginning.

21:36.867 --> 21:39.400
I think any reasonable
businessman would have...

21:39.433 --> 21:42.333
You know, here's a question that
has nothing to do with anything.

21:42.367 --> 21:44.533
You're working for the mob,
and you've been having

21:44.567 --> 21:46.567
some disagreements
with your business partners.

21:46.600 --> 21:48.733
Why would you ever
get in the front passenger seat

21:48.767 --> 21:50.260
when somebody else
is sitting in the back?

21:50.267 --> 21:53.500
I mean, Paulie made the same
mistake in "The Godfather."

21:53.533 --> 21:55.833
It's always like, you know,
"That's a bad seat to sit in."

21:55.867 --> 21:56.833
Yeah.

22:08.500 --> 22:09.000
♪

23:32.700 --> 23:33.200
♪

23:59.367 --> 23:59.867
♪

24:27.500 --> 24:28.000
♪

24:42.867 --> 24:43.367
♪

24:53.367 --> 24:53.867
♪

24:58.100 --> 24:59.867
It is tempting to think,

24:59.900 --> 25:01.533
when reflecting on
Jackson Heights,

25:01.567 --> 25:02.833
of India.

25:02.867 --> 25:06.400
But Queens is always changing,
always in flux,

25:06.433 --> 25:09.200
a landing spot for people
from all over the world;

25:09.233 --> 25:12.467
new arrivals from Tibet
being an example.

25:12.500 --> 25:13.000
♪

25:17.567 --> 25:19.700
Sandwiched between
two cell phone stores

25:19.733 --> 25:21.667
and a couple of jewelry shops

25:21.700 --> 25:24.500
is Lhasa Fast Food.

25:24.533 --> 25:27.333
This particular neighborhood
we're in now, Jackson Heights,

25:27.367 --> 25:30.800
has historically been the first
stop for the newest immigrants.

25:30.833 --> 25:32.300
It's a big Latino neighborhood,

25:32.333 --> 25:34.193
but the South Asian community's
presence is pretty well known.

25:34.200 --> 25:35.533
And it's, I think, very fitting

25:35.567 --> 25:38.133
that now this huge Tibetan
community, which is very new,

25:38.167 --> 25:39.700
looking for a home;
where they gonna go?

25:39.733 --> 25:41.193
They're gonna go
near the Indians, right?

25:41.200 --> 25:42.700
So you guys grew up together?

25:42.733 --> 25:44.533
Yeah, we grew up together
in Queens.

25:44.567 --> 25:46.567
I remember we were
in the same Little League.

25:46.600 --> 25:48.060
What position did you play
in Little League?

25:48.067 --> 25:49.060
Oh, they put me in the outfield.

25:49.067 --> 25:50.033
I was terrible.

25:50.067 --> 25:51.700
Which outfield?
That matters.

25:51.733 --> 25:53.467
Oh, yeah,
usually the right side or...

25:53.500 --> 25:54.693
- Right field?
- What do they call it?

25:54.700 --> 25:55.926
Okay, see, I don't know.
I don't know.

25:55.933 --> 25:57.900
Heems joins me for dinner

25:57.933 --> 26:00.133
along with his friend
and neighborhood advocate,

26:00.167 --> 26:01.533
Ali Najmi.

26:01.567 --> 26:03.300
Right now I'd like to call up

26:03.333 --> 26:06.233
a close friend of mine,
Mr. Ali Najmi.

26:06.267 --> 26:09.000
Thank you.

26:09.033 --> 26:10.667
I'm really involved in politics,

26:10.700 --> 26:12.533
local elections,
empowering new voters.

26:12.567 --> 26:13.900
Mm-hmm.

26:13.933 --> 26:15.826
And then advocating for
particular issues that come up.

26:15.833 --> 26:19.367
Mr. President, I know you're not
too good at listening.

26:19.400 --> 26:21.667
But you're gonna
have to hear us now.

26:23.033 --> 26:26.333
Muslim Americans
are not going anywhere.

26:28.033 --> 26:31.400
Latino Americans
are not going anywhere.

26:32.700 --> 26:34.200
And we contribute
to this country.

26:34.233 --> 26:37.200
It turns out, we pay more taxes
than you do.

26:39.533 --> 26:40.900
Why give a [...]?

26:40.933 --> 26:44.467
I have a sense
of what I think is right

26:44.500 --> 26:45.900
and what needs to be done.

26:45.933 --> 26:48.567
And I can't sit back and let
people who are being underserved

26:48.600 --> 26:50.367
continue to be underserved.

26:50.400 --> 26:51.726
You're gonna have your work
cut out for you

26:51.733 --> 26:53.526
the next four years.
We are, but you know what?

26:53.533 --> 26:54.633
Dude, we have to organize.

26:54.667 --> 26:55.967
There's no other way to do it.

26:56.000 --> 26:57.833
America wouldn't be
as great as it is right now

26:57.867 --> 26:59.367
if people didn't organize.

26:59.400 --> 27:02.867
It's both unique and disturbing
that you're also from Queens.

27:05.200 --> 27:08.333
Because the values
that you have been running on

27:08.367 --> 27:11.833
are not the Queens values
we know.

27:11.867 --> 27:13.733
And I guarantee you one thing:

27:13.767 --> 27:17.567
we, all of us, will make sure

27:17.600 --> 27:20.067
you don't forget
where you came from.

27:22.900 --> 27:25.567
How much traction are you
getting within the community?

27:25.600 --> 27:29.667
Is there a hunger for that
or is it taking some convincing?

27:29.700 --> 27:31.900
There are definitely a lot of
people who are just...

27:31.933 --> 27:33.400
Because it's such
a new community,

27:33.433 --> 27:35.067
they're just trying
to make it in America.

27:35.100 --> 27:36.760
They're trying to maximize
whatever they have,

27:36.767 --> 27:38.333
even space.

27:38.367 --> 27:40.175
"We have a cell phone store,
a phone card store.

27:40.200 --> 27:42.467
"We have a little bit of space;
let's put a restaurant here

27:42.500 --> 27:44.500
and maximize everything we can."

27:44.533 --> 27:46.633
But then there are other people
that get it,

27:46.667 --> 27:48.233
that believe
in the promise of America;

27:48.267 --> 27:49.360
they believe in their rights.

27:49.367 --> 27:49.867
♪

27:53.600 --> 27:57.167
ThenThuk: hand-torn noodle
soup with chilies and ginger.

27:57.200 --> 28:00.733
♪

28:00.767 --> 28:02.426
I mean, do you think
it's only a matter of time

28:02.433 --> 28:07.000
till you're replaced by yet
either another incoming group

28:07.033 --> 28:08.500
or, you know,

28:08.533 --> 28:10.000
uh, hipster apocalypse?

28:10.033 --> 28:11.360
Look, I mean,
the story of New York

28:11.367 --> 28:13.400
is that the neighborhoods
are constantly changing.

28:13.433 --> 28:15.667
And everything's in flux.
Nothing is static.

28:15.700 --> 28:18.667
And even all our communities
that have come in,

28:18.700 --> 28:20.667
you know, we've transformed
these neighborhoods

28:20.700 --> 28:22.167
that we've moved into.

28:22.200 --> 28:23.739
It's hard to make a claim
for ownership

28:23.767 --> 28:25.333
when my parents moved here too,
you know?

28:25.367 --> 28:26.700
So there is that constant, like,

28:26.733 --> 28:28.360
"I don't want this neighborhood
to be gentrified,

28:28.367 --> 28:30.167
but am I gentrifying it?"

28:30.200 --> 28:32.167
Shaptra, or chili fried beef:

28:32.200 --> 28:34.233
thin panes of beef
with chili oil

28:34.267 --> 28:38.333
and soy and Sichuan peppercorns.

28:38.367 --> 28:42.133
Sha momo: steamed dumplings
stuffed with beef.

28:42.167 --> 28:43.233
♪

28:43.267 --> 28:45.633
For a lot of people,
you see this community,

28:45.667 --> 28:48.167
but for them, it's like
the nightmare scenario.

28:48.200 --> 28:50.833
What's the best things about
Queens other than diversity,

28:50.867 --> 28:52.800
just as an everyday
practical matter?

28:52.833 --> 28:54.026
You wake up every day in Queens,

28:54.033 --> 28:55.533
and you're allowed to be
who you are.

28:55.567 --> 28:58.467
You can't say that
about every place;

28:58.500 --> 29:01.033
maybe not even the places
our parents come from.

29:13.100 --> 29:13.600
♪

29:20.200 --> 29:22.800
Further out in Queens,
the somewhat forlorn looking

29:22.833 --> 29:25.667
but still beautiful Rockaways.

29:31.200 --> 29:32.300
♪

29:32.333 --> 29:34.133
This is Rockaway Park.

29:34.167 --> 29:36.133
Further down,
you'd call it Far Rockaway.

29:36.167 --> 29:38.300
There's also Rockaway Beach.

29:38.333 --> 29:39.493
That's why they call it
the Rockaways

29:39.500 --> 29:40.560
and not just Rockaway sometimes.

29:40.567 --> 29:41.733
Right.

29:41.767 --> 29:43.193
There's a lot of
different parts of it.

29:43.200 --> 29:45.967
Josmar Trujillo,
a writer and local activist.

29:46.000 --> 29:47.467
You from Queens originally?

29:47.500 --> 29:49.033
I was raised in the city,

29:49.067 --> 29:52.900
but I lived in Queens
for most of my adult life now.

29:52.933 --> 29:55.033
And Rockaway now?

29:55.067 --> 29:56.633
No, so I left here a little...

29:56.667 --> 29:58.367
About a year
after Hurricane Sandy,

29:58.400 --> 30:00.633
'cause the way Sandy hit
and the way

30:00.667 --> 30:03.967
it kind of shook people
out of the way they were,

30:04.000 --> 30:05.093
and you didn't want to
put your family

30:05.100 --> 30:06.226
through that again,
the risk of that.

30:06.233 --> 30:07.733
How bad it get hit out here?

30:07.767 --> 30:11.367
This was, like,
something out of a movie.

30:11.400 --> 30:15.167
Hurricane Sandy
pounded the East Coast in 2012,

30:15.200 --> 30:16.833
and many communities suffered.

30:16.867 --> 30:21.300
But the Rockaways were hit
with particular ferocity.

30:21.333 --> 30:22.700
How was the response?

30:22.733 --> 30:24.726
Oh, you know, the response
from everyday people was good.

30:24.733 --> 30:26.133
Like, one of
the best things about

30:26.167 --> 30:27.533
what happened right afterward

30:27.567 --> 30:29.721
was the way a lot of people
came together who lived here,

30:29.733 --> 30:31.700
but also how a lot of people
kind of came in,

30:31.733 --> 30:34.633
pitched in, brought food,
brought generators.

30:34.667 --> 30:38.133
But, you know, officially, with,
like, government,

30:38.167 --> 30:40.233
the semi-governmental groups,

30:40.267 --> 30:42.467
they dropped the ball.

30:42.500 --> 30:43.693
What was the problem, though?

30:43.700 --> 30:45.567
They weren't ready for it.

30:45.600 --> 30:48.133
The Rockaways, by design has
never been a place

30:48.167 --> 30:49.667
where there was a lot of
good investment

30:49.700 --> 30:51.567
or infrastructure anyway
to begin with.

30:51.600 --> 30:53.133
Why?
Look.

30:53.167 --> 30:57.867
This is what you would call
prime oceanfront property

30:57.900 --> 31:00.533
not far from New York City.

31:00.567 --> 31:01.833
What's going on?

31:01.867 --> 31:04.367
This was a place historically
where the city

31:04.400 --> 31:07.000
and Robert Moses in particular

31:07.033 --> 31:09.967
really used as, like, a dumping
ground for undesirable groups

31:10.000 --> 31:12.000
that the city didn't necessarily
want to deal with.

31:12.033 --> 31:14.200
Back in the day,
the Rockaways were

31:14.233 --> 31:16.867
a summer destination
for middle-class New Yorkers

31:16.900 --> 31:19.533
until better roads
and an improved rail system

31:19.567 --> 31:23.033
lured them to the beaches
of Long Island.

31:23.067 --> 31:26.033
They threw a bunch of
public housing projects in here.

31:26.067 --> 31:28.200
They sent a lot of the
low-income people of the city

31:28.233 --> 31:29.967
out here,
and it just wasn't a place

31:30.000 --> 31:32.333
that historically
the city ever took seriously.

31:32.367 --> 31:34.033
You know, since then,
we've always had

31:34.067 --> 31:36.533
a lot of working-class whites
move in,

31:36.567 --> 31:38.200
into more kind of
the western end,

31:38.233 --> 31:40.467
and so you've kind of seen
in the Rockaways

31:40.500 --> 31:43.567
just kind of shape out
along race and class lines.

31:43.600 --> 31:45.867
And the one dynamic
that's changed after Sandy

31:45.900 --> 31:48.367
was that a lot more, like,
young urban professional types,

31:48.400 --> 31:49.993
like, were really coming out
here, you know,

31:50.000 --> 31:51.367
maybe looking
intentionally or not

31:51.400 --> 31:53.567
to, like,
Brooklynify the Rockaways.

31:53.600 --> 31:54.367
Right.

31:54.400 --> 31:55.900
Or gentrify the Rockaways.

31:55.933 --> 31:58.067
Rockaway's called,
like, the Brooklyn Riviera

31:58.100 --> 31:59.333
or the Williamsburg Riviera.

31:59.367 --> 32:01.333
Who gets the shaft
in a situation like that?

32:01.367 --> 32:03.967
If you're a person
who's not a homeowner;

32:04.000 --> 32:06.333
if you're a person
that's struggling to pay rent,

32:06.367 --> 32:08.667
the plans are generally,
history has told us,

32:08.700 --> 32:10.000
gonna leave you behind.

32:10.033 --> 32:11.500
It's interesting
because I don't think

32:11.533 --> 32:13.060
a lot of people thought that
that would happen here.

32:13.067 --> 32:15.567
When you're on Rockaway, you had
this kind of sense of security

32:15.600 --> 32:17.567
that you kind of were
out in this lazy beach town.

32:17.600 --> 32:19.593
And, like, I would love to come
out here and walk on the beach,

32:19.600 --> 32:21.500
and it'd be just me
and maybe two other people

32:21.533 --> 32:23.026
for miles and miles,
and that was great.

32:23.033 --> 32:24.260
Where you won't have that
anymore.

32:24.267 --> 32:25.867
Where there won't
be a place in the city

32:25.900 --> 32:27.500
for you to be able to have that.

32:27.533 --> 32:29.067
You know,
some people may be for it,

32:29.100 --> 32:31.000
and then I think
that might be shortsighted,

32:31.033 --> 32:32.426
'cause I think that this might,
uh, not necessarily

32:32.433 --> 32:34.167
involve the same
people who are here.

32:34.200 --> 32:36.333
It never does.

32:39.367 --> 32:39.867
♪

32:48.000 --> 32:50.000
What's a perfect day
in the Rockaways?

32:50.033 --> 32:52.033
Oh, a perfect day?

32:52.067 --> 32:54.000
Obviously, hit the beach,
but you don't want to

32:54.033 --> 32:56.067
find a place where there's,
you know, no sand.

32:56.100 --> 32:57.067
You know?
Right.

32:57.100 --> 32:58.200
You want to find a place

32:58.233 --> 32:59.541
that's kind of
off the beaten path.

32:59.567 --> 33:00.900
Grab a bite to eat.

33:00.933 --> 33:03.067
You maybe, you know,
have a couple of drinks at night

33:03.100 --> 33:04.467
and watch the waves crash.

33:04.500 --> 33:05.633
We're near the airport,

33:05.667 --> 33:07.026
so you watch some of the planes
fly over.

33:07.033 --> 33:09.400
And it's just, you know,
it's a different feel.

33:09.433 --> 33:11.093
You don't feel like you're in
New York when you're out here.

33:11.100 --> 33:13.567
♪

33:13.600 --> 33:15.900
When I first came here, I was...
I was a city kid.

33:15.933 --> 33:18.500
I was used to living with
the hustle and bustle

33:18.533 --> 33:20.167
of the city that never sleeps.

33:20.200 --> 33:22.067
When I got here,
there's, like, this tranquility.

33:22.100 --> 33:25.200
There's this feel
that you're not in the city,

33:25.233 --> 33:27.733
and it's great,
because it makes you feel like

33:27.767 --> 33:30.000
you can sit back
and be with your thoughts.

33:30.033 --> 33:32.333
You know, as a city kid,
it gave me a lot of perspective.

33:32.367 --> 33:35.233
So anytime you can come out here
and kind of be away from stuff

33:35.267 --> 33:37.400
and kind of be, you know,
with the water,

33:37.433 --> 33:39.000
with your thoughts,
is a great day.

33:39.033 --> 33:40.000
Yeah.

33:58.100 --> 34:02.067
♪

34:06.100 --> 34:06.600
♪

34:17.266 --> 34:17.766
♪

34:30.733 --> 34:32.199
Is that a $100 bill?

34:32.233 --> 34:33.632
Yeah.

34:33.667 --> 34:35.067
I feel dead inside, Laurie.

34:35.100 --> 34:37.667
This is gonna bring me around.

34:37.699 --> 34:40.067
Keep telling yourself that.

34:40.100 --> 34:41.300
Hi.

34:41.333 --> 34:44.132
Uh, all of it on number two
to win first.

34:44.167 --> 34:45.367
- All of it?
- Yeah.

34:46.667 --> 34:47.600
Thank you.

34:49.167 --> 34:50.193
Gotta be in it to win it,
Laurie.

34:50.199 --> 34:51.300
All right.

34:51.333 --> 34:53.733
Can I get $5 on number five
to win, please?

34:53.766 --> 34:55.632
It's the middle of winter,

34:55.667 --> 34:56.867
and there are only a few

34:56.900 --> 34:58.733
hardcore racing enthusiasts
here;

34:58.767 --> 35:01.900
also me and friend and author
Laurie Woolever.

35:01.933 --> 35:03.067
Here they come.

35:08.733 --> 35:09.700
And a winner.

35:09.733 --> 35:12.300
All right,
you won your first race.

35:12.333 --> 35:13.967
You know, you didn't
win anything, but...

35:14.000 --> 35:16.167
Not quite good enough.

35:16.200 --> 35:18.667
♪

35:18.700 --> 35:20.000
I love this place:

35:20.033 --> 35:21.867
the ponies, the beer,

35:21.900 --> 35:24.800
the looming sense of despair
and melancholy.

35:24.833 --> 35:26.667
Did I mention they have
Jamaican beef patties?

35:26.700 --> 35:28.400
So people like it here because

35:28.433 --> 35:30.467
you can get your emotional
feel for the horses

35:30.500 --> 35:32.133
and you can look down
into the paddock,

35:32.167 --> 35:35.900
and people like to sort of
see how the horse is behaving.

35:35.933 --> 35:37.733
All right.
I smell victory.

35:37.767 --> 35:39.300
Or is that horseshit?

35:39.333 --> 35:41.967
♪

35:42.000 --> 35:43.633
Fourth race, number two to win.

35:47.667 --> 35:49.567
Come on, number two!

35:49.600 --> 35:51.667
Come on!

35:51.700 --> 35:53.833
♪

35:53.867 --> 35:54.833
Oh, no!

35:56.033 --> 35:57.500
Smoked.

35:57.533 --> 35:59.467
♪

35:59.500 --> 36:00.800
I need to win
in a long shot now.

36:00.833 --> 36:02.533
I need to get well.
I gotta come back.

36:02.567 --> 36:03.800
♪

36:03.833 --> 36:05.333
Built near the site
of a former conduit

36:05.367 --> 36:07.167
for the Brooklyn Waterworks
that brought water

36:07.200 --> 36:09.833
from eastern Long Island
to the Ridgewood Reservoir,

36:09.867 --> 36:13.667
Aqueduct Racetrack
opened in 1894.

36:13.700 --> 36:16.333
The glory days of horse racing
are long gone,

36:16.367 --> 36:19.833
but for those few proud
remaining degenerate gamblers

36:19.867 --> 36:23.967
with a few bucks and a dream,
Aqueduct is still there.

36:24.000 --> 36:26.133
It's a judgment-free zone here,
though.

36:26.167 --> 36:27.467
Totally.

36:27.500 --> 36:29.333
It's kind of a "come as you
are" situation.

36:29.367 --> 36:31.800
I think that's true of Queens
in general.

36:31.833 --> 36:34.967
And you can kind of fly
under the radar, you know?

36:35.000 --> 36:38.833
You have not been harassed
too much today, right?

36:38.867 --> 36:40.133
No, a guy came up to me.

36:40.167 --> 36:41.967
He says, "Hey, you look like
Anthony Bourdain."

36:42.000 --> 36:43.667
I said,
"I wish I had his money."

36:43.700 --> 36:45.367
And he said, "Yeah, right.
That asshole."

36:45.400 --> 36:46.467
It was great.

36:46.500 --> 36:48.167
It was like
the perfect encounter.

36:48.200 --> 36:49.467
Yeah.
That's Queens.

36:49.500 --> 36:52.700
Nobody gives a shit.

36:55.733 --> 36:56.233
♪

37:08.667 --> 37:09.633
- Oh!
- All right.

37:09.667 --> 37:10.967
Two, right up on top.

37:11.000 --> 37:11.967
Yes.

37:12.000 --> 37:13.633
Come on, number two.

37:13.667 --> 37:15.500
Keep it.
Keep it.

37:15.533 --> 37:16.033
♪

37:26.233 --> 37:28.200
It's a close race.

37:28.233 --> 37:29.300
Close it up.

37:29.333 --> 37:30.300
It's a nail-biter.

37:39.833 --> 37:41.467
Dropped like a stone.

37:41.500 --> 37:43.367
Way to suck.

37:43.400 --> 37:45.800
So promising.

37:45.833 --> 37:47.667
No braces for my little girl.

37:50.233 --> 37:52.133
It's not over.

37:52.167 --> 37:53.567
There's always another race.

38:00.800 --> 38:04.500
I'm Ray.
I'm from Guyana originally.

38:04.533 --> 38:09.033
My father raced birds,
so I end up with the same hobby.

38:09.067 --> 38:11.033
It's called bird racing.

38:11.067 --> 38:12.700
Instead of, like,
a running race,

38:12.733 --> 38:14.367
it's like a singing race,
you know?

38:14.400 --> 38:18.500
The first bird to chirp to 50
won the prize.

38:18.533 --> 38:19.867
♪

38:19.900 --> 38:21.367
It's worth a lot of money.

38:21.400 --> 38:23.300
And if he become a champion,

38:23.333 --> 38:25.867
he win a couple of races,
the price goes up.

38:25.900 --> 38:28.200
$10,000, $8,000.

38:28.233 --> 38:28.733
♪

38:36.733 --> 38:38.733
Gotta be as gentle as possible.

38:38.767 --> 38:42.667
♪

38:42.700 --> 38:45.533
So I just hold it in my hand.

38:45.567 --> 38:47.967
If you hit bumps,
I rattle him, you know?

38:48.000 --> 38:51.800
I want him to be
as calm as possible.

38:51.833 --> 38:56.133
We'll find a parking as close as
possible to where we going

38:56.167 --> 39:00.200
so the birds don't be exposed
to the cold weather.

39:00.233 --> 39:00.733
♪

39:05.167 --> 39:06.867
Right now we trying to
warm up the birds.

39:06.900 --> 39:08.633
And sometimes
you bring a bird today,

39:08.667 --> 39:10.967
and he's not in the mood.

39:11.000 --> 39:11.967
Nothing happens.

39:12.000 --> 39:14.967
We just gotta another day.

39:15.000 --> 39:16.067
All right, you ready?

39:25.500 --> 39:26.000
♪

39:41.333 --> 39:43.467
♪

39:43.500 --> 39:45.133
The whole world is in Queens,

39:45.167 --> 39:48.500
and like the world as a whole,
it is constantly changing.

39:48.533 --> 39:49.800
♪

39:49.833 --> 39:51.400
Here in
the Jamaica neighborhood,

39:51.433 --> 39:54.300
a growing number of immigrants
from Africa put down roots,

39:54.333 --> 39:57.433
and with them, restaurants
catering to their tastes.

40:00.100 --> 40:03.300
Like here at Africana
restaurant.

40:03.333 --> 40:04.800
How your day?

40:07.000 --> 40:09.300
My name is Blessing Osegara.

40:09.333 --> 40:10.800
I come from Nigeria.

40:10.833 --> 40:13.967
And this one
a Nigerian restaurant.

40:14.000 --> 40:15.733
We started in 2000.

40:15.767 --> 40:18.300
The first three years were
really, really tough.

40:18.333 --> 40:19.526
But thank God were still alive,

40:19.533 --> 40:20.967
we're here
and we're [indistinct].

40:21.000 --> 40:22.967
♪

40:23.000 --> 40:25.133
My mother had a restaurant
in Nigeria

40:25.167 --> 40:27.467
for 20 years before I came here.

40:27.500 --> 40:28.967
I love to cook.

40:29.000 --> 40:31.200
When you come in here,
you feel at home.

40:31.233 --> 40:33.067
It feel like the mother's land,
you know.

40:33.100 --> 40:35.400
♪

40:35.433 --> 40:36.400
Mmm!

40:36.433 --> 40:37.467
This food is really good.

40:37.500 --> 40:38.667
It is very good.

40:38.700 --> 40:40.467
And she was worried about it
being too spicy.

40:40.500 --> 40:41.560
I don't think it's too spicy.
Oh, no.

40:41.567 --> 40:42.833
Never a problem for me.

40:42.867 --> 40:45.467
Sara Khan has made it
her mission to find

40:45.500 --> 40:47.233
and write about
some of these great little

40:47.267 --> 40:49.467
off-the-grid places
throughout the borough.

40:49.500 --> 40:53.567
You're studying the intersection
between food and culture.

40:53.600 --> 40:55.300
How did you get to that point?

40:55.333 --> 40:57.800
So I kind of cobbled together

40:57.833 --> 41:01.167
a way to travel,
learn languages, and eat.

41:01.200 --> 41:03.167
Do you ever worry
that by celebrating

41:03.200 --> 41:04.760
these communities,
you are helping to destroy them?

41:04.767 --> 41:06.567
Oh, absolutely.
Absolutely.

41:06.600 --> 41:07.800
I worry about it.

41:07.833 --> 41:09.967
But you know,
those stories need to be told

41:10.000 --> 41:11.833
through what they do,
through how they survive.

41:11.867 --> 41:14.900
♪

41:22.533 --> 41:23.033
♪

41:28.033 --> 41:31.400
Every meal,
every dish has a story,

41:31.433 --> 41:33.233
often a very personal one.

41:33.267 --> 41:37.467
Often a story of hardship,
separation, difficult times.

41:37.500 --> 41:40.400
But when somebody cooks for
you, they are saying something.

41:40.433 --> 41:42.967
They are telling you
something about themselves,

41:43.000 --> 41:44.067
where they come from,

41:44.100 --> 41:45.167
who they are,

41:45.200 --> 41:47.233
what makes them happy.

41:55.600 --> 41:57.500
A whole hell of a lot of
people in Queens,

41:57.533 --> 41:59.633
the people who
make the borough what it is,

41:59.667 --> 42:03.000
who make it such a great place
to eat and explore

42:03.033 --> 42:06.333
are very far from the places
they once called home.

42:09.367 --> 42:12.000
♪

42:12.033 --> 42:15.567
But Queens is home now.

42:21.600 --> 42:22.100
♪

